Tradescantia spathacea Sw. (= Rhoeo discolor (
<normalizedToken id="6D12E2E835793EF21134BDD602FC7021" originalValue="L’Hér">L'Her</normalizedToken>
.) Hance)
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9C757C4A8EB4EE534626D67A262D4CB4" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="names">
<paragraph id="E02F90C07B75E12C613E01F31C6C6FD3" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Names.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8AE5A818874E4BD62EDC9567D81592DE" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis id="BD7898E9328949FDC32CB675C9CE9F87" bold="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Myanmar</emphasis>
: 
<emphasis id="73CAD8FE935429EC2497E6AE2ED79AC1" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">mi-gwin-gamone</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="36661F41A692D7B8071345A253C966CD" bold="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">English</emphasis>
: boat lily, Moses in a cradle, oyster plant.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="EA3BCD7142A8506843D996E5DF95171C" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="range">
<paragraph id="D1479EB3E56BCA201DBA0F9F722EFAC4" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Range.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7B74EF42BCCE07BD923CFAA12C829F7F" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Southern Mexico, Belize, Guatemala and West Indies. Grows throughout Myanmar; cultivated.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5B1070D2F7FDFF6BF03B7521099C9473" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="uses">
<paragraph id="EC964664A4F1951BACB9E1914B16A13C" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Uses.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E5BB519E1CBBAAEBF70E31269D427AEA" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis id="ABEDF2ED470C32DEDDB7D01601A2BDF9" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Whole plant</emphasis>
: One teaspoon of the liquid obtained from pounding the plant mixed with a little sugar (taken three times a day) used to cure coughs and loosen mucus. 
<emphasis id="66B59CFCCBB83E81ED5CD39E00921978" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Stem</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="5EB963499F36424F13E204481D5424CF" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Leaf</emphasis>
: Liquid obtained from boiling crushed stems and leaves down to 1/3, together with a little raw sugar (1 tablespoon taken three times a day), used to treat vomiting of blood. 
<emphasis id="FE421AE23564E3F03993821309CA4EF5" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Leaf</emphasis>
: Used to remedy burns, scalds, and dysentery.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B47EBB9C0C0EB3BA72BB0B71A194B2F9" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="notes">
<paragraph id="30F36F392CF222F6E43C633846696322" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E8D12362BD56E1DC75F7ECFDD1CCE922" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
In China the plant is used as a poultice on swellings and wounds; the flower is used to treat dysentery, enterorrhagia, and hemoptysis (
<bibRefCitation id="9C15826DAF5C914A361A5A77F2874F15" author="Duke, JA" journalOrPublisher="Lipid / Fett" pageId="172" pageNumber="173" refId="B34" refString="Duke, JA, Ayensu, ES, 1985. Medicinal Plants of China. 2 Vols. Reference Publications, Inc., Algonac." title="Medicinal Plants of China. 2 Vols. Reference Publications, Inc., Algonac." year="1985">Duke and Ayensu 1985</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
